"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 1–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2chronicles-1-5.py

Ch1: Solomon's request for wisdom at Gibeon — Col 2:3; Jas 1:5; the gift of servant-wisdom
Ch2: Temple purpose and paradox — John 2:19-21; Acts 7:48; the body as true temple
Ch3: Mount Moriah → the Passion site tradition; the veil → Matt 27:51; Most Holy Place → Heb 9
Ch4: Bronze sea → Rev 4:6; lampstands → Rev 1:12-13; temple furnishings as types
Ch5: Glory cloud fills the temple → John 1:14; priests cannot stand → Rev 1:17

mkt-christ requires an entry for every verse (88 total).
Architectural/list verses receive brief typological notes; key Christological pivot-verses receive fuller entries.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Solomon strengthened himself (<em>wayyitkazzēq</em>) on his throne as the Davidic heir — the same verb YHWH uses when charging Joshua and the same David used when charging Solomon (1 Chr 22:13). The Chronicler's opening frames Solomon's reign as a continuation of the covenant-strengthening that is always YHWH's gift to the heir. In Christ the pattern is fulfilled: the Davidic Son who is strengthened through resurrection and enthroned at the right hand (Eph 1:20-21), all Israel's king from the first moment of his establishment.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Solomon spoke to all Israel' — the Chronicler consistently presents the Davidic king as addressing the unified covenant community. Christ as the fulfillment of Solomon addresses 'all Israel' in the eschatological sense: calling the lost sheep of Israel first (Matt 10:6), then the nations, gathering the one flock under one shepherd (John 10:16; Eph 2:11-22).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The pilgrimage to the high place at Gibeon — the legitimate sanctuary where Moses' tent of meeting still stood with Bezalel's bronze altar. The Chronicler's careful note about why Gibeon was lawful (v. 4: the ark was in Jerusalem) explains the divided worship geography before the temple. Christ transcends both Gibeon and Jerusalem: 'the hour is coming when you will worship the Father neither on this mountain nor in Jerusalem' (John 4:21), because in him all worship is now gathered.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David had brought the ark to Jerusalem; but the bronze altar of Bezalel remained at Gibeon. The separation of ark and altar before Solomon's temple is a divided-glory state the temple will resolve. Christ unites what was divided: in his body both the presence of God (ark) and the sacrifice (altar) converge — 'the Lamb who is the lamp of it' (Rev 21:23), both priest and sacrifice at once.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The bronze altar Bezalel made stands at Gibeon — connecting Solomon's worship directly to Moses' tabernacle tradition. The bronze altar is the place where the covenant's atonement logic was enacted. Christ is the final bronze altar: 'we have an altar from which those who serve the tent have no right to eat' (Heb 13:10), the sacrifice that supersedes every previous altar.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Solomon offered a thousand burnt offerings on the bronze altar — the massive scale of his worship before receiving wisdom. The generosity of Solomon's sacrifice precedes the gift. Christ offered himself once for all (Heb 7:27) — not a thousand sacrifices but one of infinite worth, the single offering that perfects forever those who are sanctified (Heb 10:14).</p>",
    "7": "<p>YHWH appeared to Solomon at night with the open offer: 'Ask what I shall give you.' The unrestricted divine offer is the grace-form of sovereign generosity. Christ makes the same unrestricted offer in John 14:13-14: 'Whatever you ask in my name, this I will do.' The pattern — divine offer, human request, gracious grant — is fulfilled when prayer is made in the name of the one greater than Solomon (Matt 12:42).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Solomon begins by acknowledging YHWH's <em>ḥesed</em> to David: 'you have shown great steadfast love to David my father.' Before asking anything, he locates himself within the covenant history. Christ is both the recipient and the fullness of this covenant loyalty — 'the sure mercies of David' (Isa 55:3; Acts 13:34), the one in whom all of YHWH's <em>ḥesed</em> to the Davidic line finds its irreversible confirmation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Let your word to David my father now be confirmed.' Solomon's prayer appeals to the Davidic promise as its foundation. The promise is confirmed not in Solomon's temple but in the resurrection of Christ — Peter's Pentecost sermon explicitly makes this link: God swore to David that 'one of his descendants' would sit on his throne, 'he foresaw and spoke about the resurrection of the Christ' (Acts 2:30-31).</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Give me wisdom and knowledge that I may lead out and bring in this great people of yours.' Solomon's request — wisdom for servant-leadership, not personal advantage — is the type of Christ's incarnational purpose. 'In him are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge' (Col 2:3): the wisdom Solomon received in part, Christ possesses in fullness. The servant-request also prefigures the principle Jesus states in Matt 20:26-28: greatness in his kingdom is measured by service.</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH commends Solomon for not asking for riches, honor, long life, or the death of enemies — for choosing wisdom for others over goods for himself. Christ fulfills the antitype fully: he 'did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped, but emptied himself' (Phil 2:6-7), choosing the servant-form. The one who had all chose the posture of not-grasping.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Wisdom and knowledge are granted to you, and I will also give you riches, possessions, and honor.' The sequence — seek first the kingdom-purpose, and all other things are added — is the pattern of Matt 6:33. Solomon receives the horizontal goods (riches, honor) as consequence of the vertical choice (wisdom). Christ is the one who 'became poor so that you by his poverty might become rich' (2 Cor 8:9) — riches given through self-emptying, not through self-seeking.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Solomon returned from Gibeon to Jerusalem, from the tent of meeting to the throne. The transition from tent-worship to enthroned rule marks the beginning of the temple period. Christ makes the analogous transition in Heb 10:12-13: from offering himself (tent-sacrifice) to sitting at the right hand (enthronement), 'waiting until his enemies are made a footstool.'</p>",
    "14": "<p>Solomon's chariot and horsemen accumulation begins the description of his material wealth. Deut 17:16 warned the future king not to multiply horses. Solomon's gathering prefigures the kingdom-of-this-world temptation that Christ refused in the wilderness (Matt 4:8-10): all the kingdoms and their glory, offered and declined. The true king's power is not in chariots (Ps 20:7).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Silver and gold made common as stones in Jerusalem — the prosperity of the Solomonic age anticipating the new creation's abundance: 'its gates will never be shut by day' (Rev 21:25); 'the kings of the earth will bring their glory into it.' The new Jerusalem fulfills what Solomon's Jerusalem only sketched.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Horses imported from Egypt — Solomon's commerce with Egypt signals the beginning of his entanglement with the world-system Deuteronomy warned against (17:16-17). Christ alone navigates the temptation without capitulation: he does not accumulate the world's symbols of power; 'my kingdom is not of this world' (John 18:36).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The pricing list for horses and chariots — Solomon as international broker between Egypt and the Hittite and Aramean kings. Christ is the true broker between heaven and earth, the one mediator (1 Tim 2:5) through whom all divine gifts are mediated — not for commercial exchange but through self-giving.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>Solomon's purpose: to build a house for YHWH's name and a palace for himself. The Name-theology — the temple is the dwelling of the <em>šēm</em> — is the OT framework for divine presence mediated through a representative location. Christ makes the Name-theology personal: 'I have made your name known to them' (John 17:26); he is the Name-bearer in whom the fullness of YHWH's character dwells (Col 1:19).</p>",
    "2": "<p>70,000 burden-bearers and 80,000 stone-cutters conscripted for the building work. The massive labor force reflects the magnitude of the building project. Christ builds his church (Matt 16:18) through willing servants, the stones being believers themselves: 'like living stones, you are being built up as a spiritual house' (1 Pet 2:5).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The letter to Huram of Tyre — Gentile international cooperation for the temple project. The temple's construction required Gentile participation — an OT anticipation of Gentile inclusion in the eschatological temple: 'foreigners who join themselves to the LORD... these I will bring to my holy mountain' (Isa 56:6-7; Eph 2:19-22).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The temple's purpose: to burn fragrant incense, offer continual bread, present burnt offerings morning and evening, Sabbaths and appointed feasts. The perpetual worship rhythms find their fulfillment in Christ, who 'always lives to make intercession' (Heb 7:25) and in the new creation worship where there is no night (Rev 22:5).</p>",
    "5": "<p>'The house that I am to build will be great, for our God is greater than all gods.' The temple's greatness is derived from YHWH's incomparability. But the greater temple is Christ's body: 'something greater than the temple is here' (Matt 12:6). All the temple's greatness was pointing toward the greater-than-Solomon who would be the true dwelling place of deity.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Who is able to build him a house, since heaven, even highest heaven, cannot contain him?' The temple's construction is preceded by its own impossible paradox — YHWH cannot be housed. Stephen quotes this logic (Acts 7:48-49) to show that the temple was never a final solution. The paradox resolves in Christ: 'in him the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily' (Col 2:9) — not in a building but in a Person.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Solomon requests a skilled craftsman — a Bezalel-figure trained in all materials and engraving. The spirit-endowed craftsman who serves the temple is the OT type of the Spirit-gifted builder in the NT: 'to each is given the manifestation of the Spirit for the common good' (1 Cor 12:7) — every gift directed toward building the temple that is the body of Christ (Eph 4:12-16).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Timber from Lebanon — cedar, cypress, and algum. The best materials from the whole known world gathered to build YHWH's house. The eschatological temple in Rev 21 is built from imperishable materials — gold, jasper, precious stones — because its builder is God (Heb 11:10).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The house I am to build will be great and wonderful.' Christ is the fulfillment of divine wonder-building: 'we beheld his glory, glory as of the only Son from the Father, full of grace and truth' (John 1:14). The temple's wonder was a reflected glory; the incarnation is the direct radiance of the Father's glory (Heb 1:3).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The wages for Tyrian workers: wheat, barley, wine, and oil. Christ provides not commodities but himself: 'I am the bread of life' (John 6:35), 'I am the true vine' (John 15:1) — the temple-builder who feeds those who labor in his service with the substance of his own person.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Huram's response: 'Because the LORD loves his people, he has made you king over them.' A Gentile king's acknowledgment that Israel's king stands under divine favor. The nations' recognition of YHWH's love for Israel is the eschatological pattern: 'all the nations shall come and worship before you' (Rev 15:4), acknowledging the LORD's righteous acts.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Huram praises 'the LORD God of Israel, who made heaven and earth.' The Gentile king confesses the Creator — a remarkable acknowledgment from outside the covenant. Paul makes this the basis of universal accountability (Rom 1:20) and the ground of mission (Acts 17:24). Christ is the one through whom all things were made (Col 1:16); Gentile praise of the Creator finds its fullest form in worship of the Son through whom creation came.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Huram-abi is sent — a skilled craftsman who mirrors Bezalel in skill: engraving, carpentry, metalwork. The craftsman who bridges ethnic boundaries to serve the temple is a type of the Spirit-gifted servant in the one body 'where there is not Greek and Jew, circumcised and uncircumcised' (Col 3:11) — all serving the building up of the one temple.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Huram-abi's mixed heritage — his mother from Dan/Naphtali in Israel, his father Tyrian — echoes Bezalel (Judah) and Oholiab (Dan) working together on the tabernacle. The body of Christ is built from every tribe and tongue (Rev 7:9; 1 Cor 12:12-14), each contributing what the Spirit has given.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The Tyrians will send timber to Joppa; Solomon will carry it to Jerusalem. The new creation's building project draws from 'the glory and honor of the nations' being brought into it (Rev 21:26) — the entire harvest of human achievement gathered into the city whose builder and architect is God.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Cedar rafted from Lebanon to Joppa (Yafo) — the port that will later receive Peter's vision of Gentile inclusion (Acts 10). The same harbor where Gentile timber arrives for the temple becomes the place where the vision of Gentile participation in God's people is given. Sacred geography carries typological freight across the biblical narrative.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The census of aliens in the land — 153,600 non-Israelites conscripted for the building project. Aliens building YHWH's house prefigures the eschatological reality: 'you are no longer strangers and aliens, but you are fellow citizens with the saints and members of the household of God, built on the foundation of the apostles and prophets, Christ Jesus himself being the cornerstone' (Eph 2:19-20).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Distribution of labor: 70,000 burden-bearers, 80,000 stone-cutters, 3,600 overseers. The organized workforce for temple-building. Christ appoints diverse gifts for building his church — apostles, prophets, evangelists, pastors, teachers (Eph 4:11-12) — each with a specific function in the construction project that continues 'until we all attain to the unity of the faith' (Eph 4:13).</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>Solomon began building 'on Mount Moriah, where YHWH had appeared to David his father, at the place that David had appointed, on the threshing floor of Ornan the Jebusite.' The mountain specification is the Chronicler's unique addition: Moriah connects the temple site to Gen 22 (Abraham's near-sacrifice of Isaac on 'one of the mountains' in the land of Moriah). The temple is built on the mountain of substitution — where the ram replaced Isaac — and tradition from the early church period locates Golgotha in the same Jerusalem hill complex. Sacrifice, substitution, divine provision, and resurrection are all concentrated at the same sacred geography.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The construction begins in the second month of Solomon's fourth year. The precision of the date anchors the typological narrative in history. The temple-building required preparation, materials, and a chosen moment — Christ's incarnation similarly came 'when the fullness of time had come' (Gal 4:4), the divinely appointed moment after centuries of preparation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The foundations: sixty cubits long, twenty cubits wide — exactly double the tabernacle's dimensions (30 × 10 cubits). The doubling signals escalation — not replacement but fulfillment. 'Something greater than the temple is here' (Matt 12:6): Christ is not merely the temple-in-double but its complete transcendence.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The vestibule (<em>ʾûlām</em>) — the transition space between outside and inside, court and sanctuary. Christ is the transition point: 'I am the door. If anyone enters by me, he will be saved' (John 10:9); all access to the Father passes through the one who stood as the gateway between profane and sacred.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The main hall paneled with cypress and overlaid with gold — gold adorning the organic wood. The combination of organic material (wood) and precious covering (gold) suggests the union of humanity and divinity — a material type of the incarnation in which deity clothes humanity, or rather in which divine and human natures are united in one person.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Precious stones from Parvaim set into the walls for beauty. The temple's interior beauty is not utilitarian but aesthetically intentional. The new Jerusalem descends 'prepared as a bride adorned for her husband' (Rev 21:2); its beauty is not ornamentation but the intrinsic glory of God dwelling there.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Gold overlay — ceiling, beams, thresholds, walls, doors all overlaid. Gold in the temple functions as light-material, catching and reflecting the lampstand's flame throughout the interior. Christ is 'the radiance of the glory of God' (Heb 1:3) — not reflecting another's light but the source of divine radiance itself.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Most Holy Place (<em>qōḏeš haqqŏḏāšîm</em>) — 20 × 20 cubits, overlaid with 600 talents of gold. This innermost chamber, where the ark would rest under the cherubim, was accessible only to the high priest once a year (Lev 16). Hebrews 9:3-8 treats this as the type Christ fulfills: he entered 'not into holy places made with hands, which are copies of the true things, but into heaven itself, now to appear in the presence of God on our behalf' (Heb 9:24).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The upper chambers overlaid with gold; the nails were of gold, fifty shekels per nail. Even the fasteners are gold — every structural element contributes to the unified whole. The new creation: 'I saw no temple in the city, for its temple is the Lord God the Almighty and the Lamb' (Rev 21:22). In the eschatological city the entire space is holy of holies.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Two sculptured cherubim overlaid with gold stand in the Most Holy Place, guarding the divine throne-space. Christ entered through the guarded threshold of the holy of holies by his own blood (Heb 10:19-20); the cherubim that barred Eden's entry (Gen 3:24) now yield to the one whose blood speaks a better word than Abel's (Heb 12:24).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Each cherub's wingspan was five cubits; the total wingspan of both cherubim together spanned the entire twenty-cubit Most Holy Place. In Rev 5:6 the Lamb stands 'in the midst of the throne' surrounded by the four living creatures — the glorified counterparts of the cherubim — as the one worthy to open the scroll of human history.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The second cherub's outer wing touched the opposite wall while its inner wing touched the first cherub's wing — the two forming one continuous canopy. The unified cherubim-canopy over the ark represents divine protection over the covenant. 'He will cover you with his feathers; under his wings you will find refuge' (Ps 91:4) — a poetic form of the same image Christ fulfills: 'how often I desired to gather your children... as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings' (Matt 23:37).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The cherubim stood on their feet, facing the nave — outward, toward approaching worshippers. The guards face the people, not away from them. Christ, as the great high priest, does not turn away from the approach of sinners: 'he is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, since he always lives to make intercession for them' (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The veil (<em>pārōḵet</em>) — made of blue, purple, and crimson fabrics with woven cherubim — separated the main hall from the Most Holy Place. The tearing of the temple veil at Christ's death (Matt 27:51) is the definitive end of this separation: 'we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus, by the new and living way that he opened for us through the curtain, that is, through his flesh' (Heb 10:19-20). The veil torn = the flesh broken = access opened.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The two pillars Jachin and Boaz — their names (<em>Jachin</em> = 'he establishes'; <em>Boaz</em> = 'in him is strength') form a confessional pair. Christ fulfills both: 'on this rock I will build my church' (Matt 16:18) — the establishment; 'I can do all things through him who strengthens me' (Phil 4:13) — the strength.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Chains in the inner sanctuary and 100 pomegranates on each chain — the same ornamental fruit-forms adorning the high priest's robe (Exod 28:33-34), linking priestly vestments to the temple's architectural decoration. Priest and temple are one system — pointing toward Christ who is simultaneously the priest and the temple (John 2:21; Heb 4:14).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The pillars set before the temple — Jachin on the south, Boaz on the north. Every approach to the temple passed between these confessional pillars: 'established / in-strength.' Rev 3:12 uses the pillar-image for the overcomer: 'I will make him a pillar in the temple of my God.' Christ is both the pillar-establisher and the one who grants pillar-status to those who conquer in him.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The bronze altar: 20 × 20 cubits square and 10 cubits high — the place of substitutionary sacrifice, the structural center of Israel's atonement system. Christ is 'the altar from which those who serve the tent have no right to eat' (Heb 13:10) — the sacrifice and the altar converged in one person, the one offering that rendered all others obsolete.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The bronze sea: 10 cubits diameter, 5 cubits high, 30 cubits circumference — a massive cleansing basin for priestly washing. Before anyone could approach the altar or enter the sanctuary, washing was required. Christ cleanses: 'he gave himself up for her, that he might sanctify her, having cleansed her by the washing of water with the word' (Eph 5:25-26).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Under the rim of the bronze sea were two rows of gourds — the vegetation motifs of the tabernacle and the garden-of-Eden symbolism embedded in the temple's design. The original garden had water (Gen 2:10); the temple sea perpetuates the water-of-life motif; Christ is 'the spring of water welling up to eternal life' (John 4:14).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The sea rested on twelve oxen — three facing each direction of the compass, supporting the basin. The twelve oxen = twelve tribes of Israel: the covenant people bearing the cleansing waters. In the new creation, the 'river of the water of life' flows from the throne of God and of the Lamb (Rev 22:1-2) — not supported by twelve oxen but flowing from the enthroned Christ himself.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The sea held 3,000 baths — vastly exceeding daily need. The abundance of cleansing water: 'the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin' (1 John 1:7). The all-inclusive 'all sin' is the NT equivalent of the sea's excessive capacity — more than enough for every worshipper who approaches.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Ten lavers for washing what pertained to burnt offerings; the sea for the priests to wash in. The lavers cleanse the sacrifices; the sea cleanses the priests. Christ purifies both: his body (the true sacrifice) was 'holy, innocent, unstained' (Heb 7:26); and 'you are already clean because of the word I have spoken to you' (John 15:3).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ten golden lampstands — five on the south side, five on the north — illuminate the interior. Christ is 'the light of the world' (John 8:12); in Rev 1:12-13, John sees 'seven golden lampstands, and in the midst of the lampstands one like a son of man' — Christ walking among his churches who are themselves lampstands (Rev 1:20), the light-bearing communities that reflect his light.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Ten tables and 100 golden basins. The tables hold the bread of the presence; the basins hold sacrificial blood. Both together constitute the covenant meal-system: presence (bread) through atonement (blood). Christ fulfills both at the Last Supper: 'this is my body' / 'this is my blood of the covenant' — the bread-and-cup that the temple's tables and basins anticipated.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The courts — great court and court of the priests — with their bronze-overlaid doors. The courts provide graduated access: outer court for Israel; inner court for priests. Christ removes this gradation: 'there is neither Jew nor Greek... for you are all one in Christ Jesus' (Gal 3:28). In the new Jerusalem there are no restricted courts — 'its gates will never be shut by day' (Rev 21:25).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The sea placed on the southeast side — the cleansing basin encountered early in the approach sequence. The gospel similarly presents cleansing before access: forgiveness precedes the feast of the presence; baptism marks entry into the covenant community.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Huram-abi made pots, shovels, and basins — completing all his work. 'He who began a good work in you will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ' (Phil 1:6). The Spirit-endowed builder of Christ's church completes what he starts — the eschatological building project will not be left unfinished.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The two pillars, the bowls, and the capitals — the structural and decorative coordination of pillars with their capitals represents the integration of foundation and crown. Christ is both foundation (1 Cor 3:11: 'no one can lay a foundation other than that which is laid, which is Jesus Christ') and crown (Rev 19:12: 'on his head are many diadems').</p>",
    "13": "<p>400 pomegranates for the two latticeworks — seed-bearing, fruitful ornaments. The pomegranate's seed-multiplicity is the type of the hundredfold harvest (Matt 13:23); Christ is the true vine whose branches bear much fruit (John 15:5).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The ten bases and ten lavers — every component of the temple's cleansing system has a structural foundation. The gospel's cleansing is grounded in the objective historical foundation: Christ 'died for our sins in accordance with the Scriptures' (1 Cor 15:3) — not a free-floating ritual but an act with a fixed historical and covenantal base.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The one sea and the twelve oxen under it — one source of cleansing, one covenant community bearing it. The body of Christ is similarly one body with many members (1 Cor 12:12-27), all sharing the one baptism (Eph 4:5).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Pots, shovels, forks — the practical instruments of the altar's daily work. These unglamorous tools are part of the temple's functional holiness. Christ's priestly ministry is similarly comprehensive: 'he is able to help those who are being tempted' (Heb 2:18) — no aspect of human need is too ordinary for his priestly attention.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The bronze vessels cast in the Jordan valley between Succoth and Zeredah — the same region where Jacob wrestled and the Jordan was crossed under Joshua. Sacred geography recurs: the place of crossing becomes the source of temple vessels, just as the Jordan of baptism (Matt 3:13-17) is the place of the one whose sacrifice provides the temple's cleansing.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Solomon made all these things in great quantity such that the weight of the bronze was not determined. The abundance exceeds cataloguing — the same excess of provision seen in the feeding of five thousand (twelve baskets of leftovers) and the wine at Cana (six jars filled to the brim). Christ's provision for his people consistently exceeds the measure of need.</p>",
    "19": "<p>All the vessels in the temple — the golden altar, the tables for the bread of the presence. The two gold installations — altar of incense and tables of presence — represent the two primary forms of temple communion: prayer (incense) and provision (bread). Christ is the fulfillment of both: the one who ever lives to intercede (Heb 7:25) and the bread of life who gives himself for the world (John 6:51).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The lampstands with their lamps burning continually before the inner sanctuary — the perpetual light of divine presence. Christ promises unceasing light: 'I am the light of the world. Whoever follows me will not walk in darkness' (John 8:12); in the new Jerusalem, 'the Lord God will be their light, and they will reign forever and ever' (Rev 22:5).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The flowers, lamps, and tongs of purest gold — every interior element contributing to a unified, holy space. The purity of material signifies the purity of the presence it serves. 'The city was pure gold, clear as glass' (Rev 21:18) — and 'nothing unclean will ever enter it... but only those who are written in the Lamb's book of life' (Rev 21:27).</p>",
    "22": "<p>The sockets of the temple doors — even the hinges are of gold. There is no diminishing of holiness at the threshold — the approach and the interior share the same quality of sacred presence. Christ is the door (John 10:7-9): the threshold-person who does not reduce the holiness of what lies beyond but himself constitutes the way into it.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>All the work was finished. Solomon stored the silver, gold, and vessels in the treasuries. The completion precedes the installation of the presence. 'It is finished' (John 19:30) — Christ's words from the cross mark the same completion-point before the installation of the presence: his resurrection and ascension install him as the true ark of the covenant in the heavenly holy of holies (Heb 9:24).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Solomon assembled the elders of Israel to bring the ark from Zion. The gathering of all Israel for the ark's installation is the type of the eschatological gathering: Christ will 'gather together in one the children of God who are scattered abroad' (John 11:52; Eph 1:10).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The assembly gathered at the feast in the seventh month — Sukkot (Feast of Booths/Tabernacles). The ark's installation happens during the feast that celebrated YHWH's dwelling with Israel in the wilderness. The feast of dwelling (tabernacling) is the moment when the ark enters its permanent home — the permanent tabernacling that John 1:14 announces: 'the Word became flesh and dwelt [<em>ἐσκήνωσεν</em>, pitched his tent] among us.'</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Levites carried the ark — the holy transport tradition maintained from the wilderness. The care with which the covenant container is handled reflects its gravity. Christ carries the weight of the covenant in his own person: 'he himself bore our sins in his body on the tree' (1 Pet 2:24).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The priests and Levites carried the ark, the tent of meeting, and all the holy vessels of the tent — the original tabernacle and its contents brought together with the new temple, old meeting fulfillment. The NT similarly does not discard the OT but fulfills it: 'I have not come to abolish the Law or the Prophets... but to fulfill them' (Matt 5:17).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Solomon and all the assembly sacrificed sheep and oxen that could not be counted or numbered. The uncountable sacrifices converging on this moment of the ark's installation. One sufficient sacrifice supersedes the uncountable: 'he has appeared once for all at the end of the ages to put away sin by the sacrifice of himself' (Heb 9:26).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The priests brought the ark into the Most Holy Place, under the wings of the cherubim. The ark enters its permanent resting place. Christ ascended and 'entered heaven itself, now to appear in the presence of God on our behalf' (Heb 9:24) — the true ark entered the true Most Holy Place, his appearance there being our representation before the Father.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The cherubim spread their wings over the ark — the protective, throne-canopy posture. Christ has entered under the wings of the Father's eternal love, and in him so have we: 'I give them eternal life, and they will never perish, and no one will snatch them out of my hand' (John 10:28).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The poles of the ark were so long that their ends were visible from the Holy Place in front of the Most Holy Place — but not seen from outside. The liminal visibility of the poles marks the boundary: the presence of the ark was known from the Holy Place but not beyond. In Christ the boundary shifts outward: 'the temple veil was torn in two from top to bottom' (Matt 27:51), making the invisible presence visible to all who come through the new and living way.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Nothing in the ark except the two tablets that Moses put there at Horeb — the covenant-word reduced to its essence. 'The Word became flesh' (John 1:14): the divine covenant-word that the tablets contained now inhabits a human body — the ultimate form of the Torah's embodiment.</p>",
    "11": "<p>All the priests present sanctified themselves regardless of their division assignments — on this day the normal rotation was suspended; all were holy. In Christ the universalization is total: 'you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation' (1 Pet 2:9) — all believers sanctified by the one offering (Heb 10:10).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Levitical singers — Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun and their sons and brothers — with cymbals, harps, and lyres, joined by 120 priests with trumpets. The massive musical ensemble assembled to welcome the ark. Rev 5:11-12 and 15:2-4 depict the heavenly counterpart: 'innumerable angels' and 'those who had conquered' with harps, singing the new song before the throne — the fulfillment of the temple choir's worship.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'When the trumpeters and singers made themselves heard with one voice to praise and give thanks to YHWH... the house was filled with a cloud.' The unity of the musical praise — <em>kᵉqôl ʾeḥāḏ</em>, as one voice — is the precondition for the glory cloud's arrival. The cloud of YHWH's glory fills the house: the <em>ʿānān kāḇôḏ</em>, the visible manifestation of the divine presence. John 1:14 is its fulfillment: 'we have seen his glory, glory as of the only Son from the Father, full of grace and truth.' The cloud-glory that filled Solomon's temple now permanently dwells in the incarnate Son.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The priests could not stand to minister because of the cloud, for the glory of YHWH filled the house. The overwhelming divine presence disabled normal priestly function. This is the NT's pattern for encounter with the glorified Christ: John falls 'as though dead' before the risen Lord (Rev 1:17); Saul is struck down on the Damascus road (Acts 9:4). In each case Christ raises them: 'fear not.' The encounter with glory leads through prostration to the commissioning embrace.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in DATA.values())
    print(f'2chronicles mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses across ch 1-5')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
